In general, the drugs taken to prevent #malaria are the same drugs used to treat the disease. Your #doctor can help you evaluate your risk for #infection and prescribe the #drug that will work best on the type of malaria parasite most commonly found in that region.

#Health

‚Ä¢ Anemia. Malaria damages red blood cells, which can result in anemia.
‚Ä¢ Low #BloodSugar. Severe forms of malaria itself can cause low blood sugar (hypoglycemia), as can quinine ‚Äî common medication used to combat #malaria. Very low blood #sugar can result in coma or death.

‚Ä¢ Breathing problems. Accumulated fluid in your #lungs (pulmonary edema) can make it difficult to breathe.
‚Ä¢ Organ failure. #Malaria can cause your #kidneys or #liver to fail, or your spleen to rupture. Any of these conditions can be life-threatening.

#Health

In most cases, malaria deaths are related to complications including:
‚Ä¢ #Cerebral malaria. If parasite-filled blood cells block small blood vessels to your #brain, swelling of your brain or brain damage may occur. Cerebral #malaria may cause seizures and coma.

#HealthForAll

Complications
#Malaria can be fatal, particularly malaria caused by the variety of parasite common in tropical parts of #Africa. The Centers for Disease Control and Prevention estimates that 91% of all malaria deaths occur in Africa - common in #children under the age of 5.
